MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Replace the recursive serial exec_node with a single dependency-count scheduler
that runs independent targets' recipes concurrently in parallel brush subshells,
bounded by the engine slip pool. The Evaluator is not Send, so the make thread
keeps it and does ALL DAG-walking + command EVALUATION serially; only concrete
command strings are dispatched to worker threads (which need no Evaluator).

One implementation, not two: each node gets its DFS post-order rank (the order
the old recursion would finish it) and ready nodes are selected lowest-rank-first,
so at cap=1 the scheduler is byte-identical in execution order to the recursion.
Validated: the rkati<->make corpus stays 364/378 fail=0 at cap=1, so exec_node is
now redundant and deleted. Parallel only when -j>1 is requested or a parent
advertised a jobserver in MAKEFLAGS (a sub-make inherits parallelism, like GNU
make); plain standalone make stays serial.

Details:
- flags: `jobs_explicit` distinguishes an explicit -j from the num_jobs default.
- kati jobserver client (fifo, O_NONBLOCK) draws a slip per concurrent recipe
  beyond the one implicit job; the scheduler honors cap + pool.
- recipe cwd is threaded EXPLICITLY through the runner (RecipeRunner gains a cwd
  arg) instead of a make-thread thread-local the worker wouldn't see — fixes
  parallel recursive make building in the wrong dir.
- target-specific exported vars are applied as a non-echoed `export` prefix per
  command (process env can't be used — parallel recipes would race it).
- circular-dependency back-edges are dropped with the same warning as before.

Box CASE 11 now runs its two recursive sub-makes concurrently (two Evaluators on
two threads, no state clobber); full box suite green.

